  "text": "Previous studies have demonstrated that various cytokines and markers of immune activation correlate with the severity of dis- are negative, weak positive, and strong positive controls, respectively. P1, P2, and P3 are before, during (6 months later), and 7 months after seroconversion, respectively. NC is an HIV-1 negative-control plasma sample. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In the case presented herein, we detected elevated plasma concentrations of IL-1␤, IL-6, IL-10, and IFN-␥ during seroconversion that declined to preconversion levels 7 months later. Interestingly, we did not observe changes in the proinflammatory cytokine TNF-␣ throughout the monitoring period. A surge in proinflammatory cytokines (IL-1␤ and IL-6) can result in increased production of acute phase proteins by the liver, which in turn can play a role in inhibiting viral replication [CITATION_3] . Our inability to detect changes in TNF-␣ during acute HIV-1 infection might be related to the time period when the blood sample was collected for analysis. For instance, at least one other study failed to detect increases in TNF-␣ during acute HIV infection [CITATION_4] . It is noteworthy that in usual or representative cases of acute HIV-1 infection, the plasma concentrations of TNF-␣ are elevated at seroconversion and at follow-up MACS clinic visits (Table 1) .",
